{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ef9695db-d990-4b22-a7b7-49784039efeb","content":"There's no workflow file in the current directory, so I'll give you a general guide. Here are the key changes to switch from `secrets.NUGET_API_KEY` to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC):\n\n### 1. Configure NuGet.org\nOn **nuget.org**, go to your package → **Manage** → **Trusted Publishers** and register your GitHub repository (owner, repo, optional workflow/environment constraints).\n\n### 2. Update your GitHub Actions workflow\n\n**Add `id-token` permission** so the runner can request an OIDC token:\n\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC\n  contents: read\n```\n\n**Replace your push step.** Instead of:\n\n```yaml\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }} --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nUse the official action (or the `--api-key` flag with the token):\n\n```yaml\n- name: Push to NuGet (trusted publishing)\n  uses: dotnet/nuget-push@v1\n  with:\n    source: https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n    # No api-key needed — OIDC token is exchanged automatically\n```\n\nOr if you prefer the CLI directly with the built-in OIDC token:\n\n```yaml\n- name: Get OIDC token & push\n  run: |\n    TOKEN=$(curl -sS -H \"Authorization: bearer $ACTIONS_ID_TOKEN_REQUEST_TOKEN\" \\\n      \"$ACTIONS_ID_TOKEN_REQUEST_URL&audience=api://AzureADTokenExchange\" | jq -r '.value')\n    dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json --api-key \"$TOKEN\"\n```\n\n### 3. Remove the secret\nOnce verified, delete `NUGET_API_KEY` from your repository secrets.\n\n### Summary of changes\n| Area | Before | After |\n|---|---|---|\n| **nuget.org** | API key | Trusted publisher registered |\n| **Workflow permissions** | (none) | `id-token: write` |\n| **Push step** | `--api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }}` | OIDC via `dotnet/nuget-push` action or token exchange |\n| **Secrets** | `NUGET_API_KEY` | Can be removed |\n\nThe `dotnet/nuget-push@v1` action is the simplest path — it handles the OIDC token exchange transparently.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"019b44b4-7650-4fcc-a50c-3042f87c6e52","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory appears to be empty. There's no existing workflow file to look at. The user is asking a general question about switching from NuGet API key to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) in GitHub Actions. Let me provide guidance based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":707},"id":"4e406d90-7adb-48d8-8514-c9f706051344","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:47:10.449Z","parentId":"f499571f-a4bd-46cd-82fc-2f6928c3b703"}
